    <h2>Understanding the Types of Commercial Coffee Machines</h2>
    <p>Before diving into prices, it's worth understanding the key categories clearly — because choosing the wrong machine type is the most common and most expensive mistake café and restaurant owners make.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Semi-automatic espresso machines</strong> require a skilled barista to control dose, grind, tamp, and extraction time. They produce the highest-quality espresso but depend entirely on barista skill.</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic (volumetric) espresso machines</strong> control the water volume automatically — the barista still doses and tamps, but the machine stops extraction at the right volume. More consistent, slightly less control.</li>
      <li><strong>Super-automatic machines</strong> do everything: grind, dose, tamp, extract, and often froth milk. Minimal skill required, but less customisation. Great for offices, hotels, and fast-casual cafés.</li>
      <li><strong>Filter coffee machines</strong> brew large batches of drip coffee. They're the workhorse of hotel breakfast services, offices, and American-style cafés.</li>
      <li><strong>Bean-to-cup machines</strong> (often used synonymously with super-automatic in India) cover a spectrum from office machines to café-grade. They differ from pure super-automatics in that the "bean-to-cup" label emphasises the full grinding process.</li>
      <li><strong>Cold brew systems</strong> steep coffee grounds in cold water for 12–24 hours. Commercial systems manage this at scale with precise temperature control and nitrogen infusion options.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>1. Semi-Automatic Espresso Machines</h2>
    <p>A semi-automatic espresso machine is what most people picture when they imagine a café. Hot water is forced through a packed puck of finely ground coffee at 9 bars of pressure, producing a concentrated shot of espresso with a layer of golden crema on top. The barista controls the grind, dose, and extraction — the machine provides consistent temperature and pressure.</p>
    <p>In India, espresso culture has grown rapidly over the past decade, driven by speciality coffee chains, independent cafés in metro cities, and a younger generation that has travelled and adopted espresso-based drinks. Semi-automatic machines are now found in everything from high-end specialty coffee roasters to small neighbourhood cafés.</p>

    <h3>Single-Group Semi-Automatic Espresso Machines</h3>
    <p>A single-group machine can produce one espresso shot at a time. It's sufficient for cafés doing up to 80–120 cups per day, or for restaurants where coffee is a side offering rather than the main product.</p>
