    <h2>5. Cold Brew Coffee Equipment</h2>
    <p>Cold brew coffee has grown from a niche specialty product to a mainstream menu item in Indian cafés and QSR chains over the past three years. Cold brew is made by steeping coarse coffee grounds in cold or room-temperature water for 12–24 hours, producing a smooth, low-acid concentrate that is then diluted or served over ice.</p>
    <p>Commercial cold brew systems range from simple immersion systems (a bucket, a filter, and time) to sophisticated pressurised nitrogen-charged systems. For most Indian cafés, a mid-range commercial immersion system is the right entry point.</p>

    <h3>Commercial Cold Brew Equipment Prices</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Commercial cold brew batch system (10L–20L, SS)</strong>: ₹25,000 – ₹55,000</li>
      <li><strong>Cold brew tower (drip tower, 5L–10L)</strong>: ₹30,000 – ₹80,000</li>
      <li><strong>Nitrogen cold brew keg system (30L, with N2 tap)</strong>: ₹85,000 – ₹1,60,000</li>
      <li><strong>Commercial nitro cold brew tap system (full setup)</strong>: ₹1,50,000 – ₹3,00,000</li>
      <li><strong>Cold brew concentrate dispenser (chilled, countertop)</strong>: ₹45,000 – ₹90,000</li>
      <li><strong>Large-batch cold brew system (100L+, for production)</strong>: ₹2,50,000 – ₹6,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For a café adding cold brew to the menu, a commercial batch system (₹25K–₹55K) and a dedicated refrigerator for the brew is sufficient to start. Add a nitrogen keg system if you want nitro cold brew on tap — it's a high-margin, high-differentiation product.</p>

